	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EFSA assessment of the FMD threat from developing countries</h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 February 2006
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> This report reviews the threat of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) transmission to the EU herd from the trade with developing countries and what actions can be taken to minimise the risks. ‘As Europe experiences greater immigration and increased trade in commodities, particularly when transported chilled or frozen, it is likely that such factors (relating to FMD outbreaks) will become rather more important’. The greatest threat is seen to come from ‘live animals originating from the middle-east’ and from ‘south-east Asia and China and south Asia’.</p><p> ‘A sustainable FMD risk-reduction strategy for the protection of Europe will need to address not only the targeted and progressive control of FMD in the high-risk primary endemic epidemiological clusters of south-east Asia and China (Indo-China) and south Asia, which currently represent the biggest threat to Europe, but also in eastern Africa and the Sahel’. Controlling FMD in endemic areas is seen as ‘technically feasible’, requiring ‘a regional approach to disease control, setting up a global surveillance partnership, and putting together a strategy to promote safe trading’. It notes that ‘an essential condition for success is that the positive impact of the proposed measures accrues not only to the EU but also to local stakeholders at all levels’.</p><p> The report concludes ‘Europe remains vulnerable to the introduction of FMD from endemic disease areas outside its borders. In the context of increasing globalisation with increasing imports of animals and animal products into the EU, not to mention the expansion of the borders of the EU itself, the risk from both legal and illegal activities is likely to increase’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Summary EFSA report and point of access for full report (February 5th 2006) </p><p>

<a href="http://www.efsa.eu.int/science/ahaw/ahaw_opinions/1357_en.html" target="_self">http://www.efsa.eu.int/science/ahaw/ahaw_opinions/1357_en.html</a> <br /> Europa/development cooperation by region: Lomé</p><p>

<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/development/body/publications/rep98/regio_en.htm" target="_self">http://europa.eu.int/comm/development/body/publications/rep98/regio_en.htm</a> <br /> Regional allocations: Cotonou</p><p>

<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/development/body/csp_rsp/rsp_en.cfm" target="_self">http://europa.eu.int/comm/development/body/csp_rsp/rsp_en.cfm</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The report implicitly calls for a strengthening of EU efforts in support of FMD control in third countries. This was traditionally a focus of EU assistance through its regionally programmed aid to ACP countries. However, in recent years the percentage of the total regional allocation under ACP-EU cooperation agreements being allocated to programmes of functional regional cooperation such as FMD-control programmes has declined dramatically. With the policy emphasis for regional programmes increasingly on trade-policy measures, it remains to be seen where funds for expanded support for FMD control in ACP countries will come from. A dedicated financial facility may well be needed, particularly if, as recommended, measures must benefit ‘local stakeholders at al levels’.</p><p><b>Regional allocations to specific regions from funds set aside for regional cooperation (millions ecu/euro)</b> </p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
